{"add":{"doc":{"id":"cca75faa58e17a377a781e8c7540786de9951929a023eb4e4200d8d82376e8d7","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/Manfred_von_Richthofen.jpg/170px-Manfred_von_Richthofen.jpg","previous":[],"after":["World War I introduced the systematic use of true single-seat fighter aircraft, with enough speed and agility to catch and maintain contact with targets in the air, coupled with armament sufficiently powerful to destroy the targets. Aerial combat became a prominent feature with the Fokker Scourge, in the last half of 1915. This was also the beginning of a long-standing trend in warfare, showing statistically that approximately five percent of combat pilots account for the majority of air-to-air victories.[1]"]}}}